\lang english
Effective:
 July 01,
 2026
\begin_inset space \hfill{}
\end_inset

Version:
 1.0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
1.
 Purpose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy establishes the mandatory requirements for the generation,
 protection,
 review,
 and retention of security audit logs across all Elko County information systems.
 It ensures that system activity is continuously recorded and monitored to detect unauthorized access,
 support forensic investigations,
 maintain individual accountability,
 and fulfill the strict audit and accountability mandates of the FBI Criminal Justice Information Services (CJIS) Security Policy and Nevada Revised Statutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
2.
 Scope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy applies to all Elko County information systems,
 network infrastructure,
 endpoints,
 and cloud services that process,
 store,
 or transmit County data.
 It governs the configurations,
 aggregation systems (e.g.,
 SIEM),
 and personnel responsible for security event logging.
 Operational performance logging (e.g.,
 resource utilization metrics) is explicitly out of scope for this policy and is governed under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Monitoring and Event Management Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
3.
 Roles and Responsibilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
IT Director
\series default
:
 Shall serve as the final authority on audit logging requirements,
 ensure configurations for systems processing Criminal Justice Information (CJI) meet federal mandates,
 and serve as the delegated Information Operations Records Custodian for IT-managed data assets.
 The IT Director shall designate a Records Liaison responsible for maintaining the exact mapping between system log types and the Nevada retention schedule record series (LRDA 20071728).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Assistant IT Director
\series default
:
 Shall oversee the centralized log management architecture,
 allocate sufficient storage capacity,
 ensure automated audit review mechanisms are configured to alert on anomalous activities,
 coordinate incident response activities triggered by audit findings,
 and ensure the mandated weekly review of aggregated security audit logs is conducted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
System and Network Administrators
\series default
:
 Shall configure information systems to generate required audit records,
 forward those records to the centralized log repository,
 review automated security alerts in accordance with established SLAs,
 and protect log facilities from unauthorized access.
 To comply with separation of duties,
 personnel administering security access controls shall not possess the capability to modify or delete the audit logs that record their actions,
 nor shall they be the sole reviewers of their own administrative logs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Department Heads (Data Owners)
\series default
:
 Shall identify any specific business or regulatory logging requirements applicable to their departmental data and coordinate implementation with the Information Operations Department.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
All Personnel
\series default
:
 Shall not disable,
 bypass,
 or tamper with system auditing functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
4.
 Compliance and Exceptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Mandatory Enforcement:
 Compliance with this policy is mandatory.
 The intentional disablement,
 circumvention,
 or alteration of audit logging mechanisms by unauthorized personnel constitutes a severe security violation and shall result in immediate access revocation and disciplinary action,
 up to and including termination and criminal referral under NRS 205.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Exceptions:
 Exceptions shall be documented in a formal Risk Acceptance Memo,
 including defined compensating controls and an expiration date not to exceed twelve (12) months,
 and must be approved in writing by the IT Director in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Any exception affecting systems that process CJI shall require explicit written approval from the CJIS Systems Officer (CSO) prior to implementation.
\end_layout

