\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Auditable Events (Event Generation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall configure all County information systems,
 network infrastructure,
 and cloud environments to generate audit records for security-relevant events.
 At a minimum,
 the following events shall be logged:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Authentication and Access
\series default
:
 All successful and unsuccessful logon attempts,
 session disconnections,
 and access to systems processing Criminal Justice Information (CJI) or Restricted County data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Privileged Operations
\series default
:
 All actions executed under elevated or administrative privileges (Tier L3 and above),
 including "break-glass" emergency access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Account Management
\series default
:
 The creation,
 modification,
 enablement,
 disablement,
 and deletion of any system or user account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Data Manipulation
\series default
:
 The creation,
 modification,
 and deletion of Restricted data (including CJI) and Confidential data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Security Control Modifications
\series default
:
 Any modification to security baselines,
 firewall rules,
 group policies,
 or audit logging configurations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
System Integrity
\series default
:
 System restarts,
 shutdowns,
 and alerts generated by malicious code protection or file integrity monitoring (FIM) mechanisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Content of Audit Records
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To ensure forensic viability and individual accountability,
 every generated audit record shall contain the following mandatory data elements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Timestamp
\series default
:
 The exact date and time the event occurred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Identity
\series default
:
 The unique identifier (e.g.,
 username,
 service account ID) of the individual or process causing the event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Event Type
\series default
:
 A clear categorization of the action attempted or executed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Outcome
\series default
:
 An indicator of success or failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Originating Source
\series default
:
 The logical and/or physical origin of the request (e.g.,
 source IP address,
 MAC address,
 terminal identifier).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Target Asset
\series default
:
 The name,
 ID,
 or file path of the system,
 application,
 or data record impacted by the event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Log Centralization,
 Capacity,
 and Tamper Protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To satisfy separation of duties and protect audit integrity,
 audit logs shall be protected from unauthorized modification,
 deletion,
 and spoofing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Storage Capacity
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall allocate sufficient audit record storage capacity to prevent logs from being overwritten or dropped prior to their scheduled archival.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Centralized Repository
\series default
:
 Systems shall forward audit records continuously,
 or at highly frequent intervals,
 to a centralized,
 logically isolated log management repository (e.g.,
 SIEM).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Append-Only Enforcemen
\series default
t:
 Personnel with administrative control over security baselines or system configurations shall not have the ability to modify or delete audit logs that record their actions.
 The centralized repository shall enforce append-only or read-only privileges for all system and network administrators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Tamper Detection
\series default
:
 The central log repository shall employ cryptographic mechanisms (e.g.,
 file hashing) or strict access control monitoring to detect unauthorized modifications to archived log files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Audit Review,
 Analysis,
 and Alerting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall proactively analyze audit records to detect anomalous activity,
 unauthorized access attempts,
 and potential security incidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Review Frequency
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure designated Tier L3 personnel conduct a formal review of aggregated security audit logs at least weekly to identify anomalous patterns that may not trigger automated alerts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Automated Alerting
\series default
:
 The Department shall employ automated tools configured to generate real-time alerts for critical security events,
 including but not limited to:
 multiple failed authentication attempts,
 unauthorized access to CJI repositories,
 and detection of malicious code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Alert Routing
\series default
:
 System-generated security alerts shall be transmitted to the Assistant IT Director and designated Tier L3 System Administrators in real-time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Alert Review SLA
\series default
:
 Alerts generated by the automated system shall be reviewed by designated Tier L3 Administrators within four (4) business hours of generation during standard operating hours,
 or by the start of the next business day for off-hours alerts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Trigger
\series default
:
 Personnel shall analyze and respond to alerts in accordance with the incident declaration and response protocols defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Response to Audit Processing Failures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To ensure continuous visibility,
 the logging architecture must immediately detect and report failures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Failure Alerting
\series default
:
 The logging system shall be configured to alert the Assistant IT Director and designated Administrators within one (1) hour of an audit processing failure (e.g.,
 software/hardware errors,
 network disruption,
 or storage reaching capacity thresholds).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Restoration SLA
\series default
:
 Personnel shall initiate troubleshooting and restoration of logging functionality within one (1) hour of receiving the failure alert.
 If restoration cannot be achieved,
 the affected system may be subject to logical isolation based on its risk profile,
 as determined by the IT Director or Assistant IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Time Synchronization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To ensure accurate correlation of audit records across distinct systems,
 all County information systems and network devices shall synchronize their internal clocks to an authoritative,
 County-approved Network Time Protocol (NTP) source.
 The primary internal NTP servers shall synchronize with a trusted,
 stratum-1 external time source (e.g.,
 NIST internet time servers).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Records Retention and Disposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Audit logs constitute official County records and shall be retained in strict accordance with the Nevada Local Government Records Retention Schedule and statutory public records mandates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Retention Period
\series default
:
 IT security logs,
 including access control and audit logs,
 shall be retained for a minimum of three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year in which the review or audit was concluded.
 This standard explicitly exceeds the CJIS minimum requirement of one (1) year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Legal Hold
\series default
:
 The IT Director,
 acting as the Records Custodian,
 shall ensure all automated and manual log disposition actions are immediately suspended during active litigation holds,
 public records preservation requirements,
 audits,
 or active incident investigations.
\end_layout

